Hecate (63) says that an honest man may consult his own inteream, if he does not violate law or custom. It is true that fraud is very common (64), and thoroughly upright men are rare.

In the sale of lauded estates (XVI. 65) the law is, that defects known to the seller must be disclosed to the buyer. Claudius owned a house (66) on the Caelian hill, which hin- dered the observations of the augurs. When ordered by them to remove the obstruction he sold the house to Calpurnius, concealing the fact. Cato held him liable for damages to Calpurnius on that ground. A similar case was that of the sale of a house by M. Marius Gratidianus to O. Sergius Orata.

The laws prevent fraud only so far as it can be reached by special enactment3 but philosophers (XVII) apply the test of reason and knowledge, and these forbid all unfair dealing, prc- tence, or deecit.
